\begin_layout Subsection
One-stage Deviation Principle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A strategy profile is 
\series bold
resistant to a one stage deviation
\series default
, if there is no subgame where a player can gain by a single deviation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In every finite game, a profile is a sub-game perfect equilibrium iff it
 is resistant against a one stage deivation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Rubinstein's Model of Alternating Offer Bargaining
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a tension between the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

commitment to finite
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and the desire to continue negotiation.
 Infinite games are more natural by definition.
 This game is the best illustration to the power of subgame NE.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This game has many NE, for example demanding 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 by player 1 and acceping at least 
\begin_inset Formula $1-x$
\end_inset

 for player 2 (and vice versa) is a NE for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
NE is not useful here to predict how the game will be played.
 Consider for example, 
\begin_inset Formula $(0.7,0.3)$
\end_inset

.
 If player 1 asks some 
\begin_inset Formula $x'>0.7$
\end_inset

, player 2 is supposed to reject it and offer 
\begin_inset Formula $(0.7,0.3)$
\end_inset

 in the next round.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $0.3$
\end_inset

 in the future is worth less than 
\begin_inset Formula $0.3$
\end_inset

, thus, depending on the discount rate and 
\begin_inset Formula $x'$
\end_inset

, player 2 might be better off acceping 
\begin_inset Formula $1-x'$
\end_inset

, thus there exists such 
\begin_inset Formula $x'>0.7$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rubinstein's proposition states that this game has a unique subgame-perfect
 NE, in which player 1 always offers some 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}$
\end_inset

 and accepts at least 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{y}$
\end_inset

, and player 2 beahves the opposite, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{y}=\delta_{1}x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\bar{x}=\delta_{2}(1-\bar{y})$
\end_inset

.
 The game ends with 
\begin_inset Formula $(\bar{x},1-\bar{x})$
\end_inset

 in orund round 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This game has the property of self-similarity: the situation of player 1
 in period 1 is identical to the situation in periods 3, 5,..
 - the same is true for player 2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Looking at the payoffs, when player 1 becomes very paitent (
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{1}$
\end_inset

 is close to 1) then 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}=\frac{1-\delta_{1}}{1-\delta_{1}\delta_{2}}$
\end_inset

 which converges to 1, meaning that being patient is an advantage in negotiation
s.
 The basic intuition that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

patience is valuable and impatience is an impediment
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 holds in an equilibrium.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the players are equally patient, player 1 has little advantage, and as
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\rightarrow1$
\end_inset

, the payoffs converge to 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

